<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Finding 4 · SQL Injection</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/learn.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="learn-page">
    <div class="brand brand-sm" style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
      <span class="brand-mark">⛨</span>
      <span>CySER Workshop · Skyway engagement</span>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-hero">
      <div class="hero-icon">💉</div>
      <h1>Finding 4 confirmed</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">Day 4 · SQL Injection (auth bypass)</p>
      <div class="flag-badge"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-grid">
      <div class="learn-card skill-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📚</div>
        <h2>The vulnerability</h2>
        <h3>User input becomes code</h3>
        <p>String-concatenating user input into a SQL query means the database parser can't tell data from instructions. <code>' OR '1'='1' --</code> turns "find this exact user" into "find anyone" with two extra characters.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card world-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📰</div>
        <h2>Seen in the wild</h2>
        <h3>Decades and counting</h3>
        <p>SQL injection has been #1 on the OWASP Top 10 across multiple editions. TalkTalk (£77M fine), Heartland Payment Systems (130M cards), 7-Eleven, Sony Pictures. All SQLi. Despite being a 20+ year old bug class, it still cracks the top web vulnerability lists every year.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card career-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🛠️</div>
        <h2>How to fix it</h2>
        <h3>Parameterized queries, always</h3>
        <p><code>db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE u=? AND p=?", [u, p])</code>. The <code>?</code> placeholders mean the driver sends data separately from the query. The database can never misinterpret <code>'</code> in a username as syntax. Use an ORM, or use prepared statements. Never concatenate.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card key-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
        <h2>One-line takeaway</h2>
        <h3>Separate data from instructions</h3>
        <p>This pattern, "user input parsed as syntax by some downstream interpreter", is the root of injection bugs everywhere: SQL, NoSQL, OS commands, LDAP queries, XPath, template engines, prompt injection. Same lesson, every layer.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-nav">
      <a href="/" class="nav-btn secondary">← All findings</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %><a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="nav-btn primary">Day <%= nextNum %> →</a><% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
